This reminds me of what people used to say in the fifties/sixties/seventies, &quot;Honey, those men in Washington know what's best for us.  Otherwise, they wouldn't be there.&quot;  But politicians are not in Washington simply to achieve their own agendas, which I think Bush and his close supporters are attempting, they are there to represent the people.  But most importantly, is that a citizen has a duty to question the judgments and decisions of their elected officials.  This is important because America only functions best if it is functioning as an open forum of ideas.<br>
<br>
Kazot wrote:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>How do you account for the Republican sponsored Medication bill?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I account for it like this:  Bushites, &quot;OH NO! The president's popularity has gone down!  Quick, what do we do?!  I know, lets pass a medication bill, which really won't help anyone but the wealthy old (not the below to slightly above poverty level elderly,) since that is something the Democratic party has been fighting for for some time.  That will give us a foothold into the elderly vote as well as steal yet another campaigning point from the Democrats.&quot;<br>
I would applaud the Republicans for at least attempting to help some elderly Americans if I didn't suspect they were only doing it for purely political motives.  Actions done for the wrong motive aren't worthy of praise, at least to me.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The louder the far left yells their rant the more people vote conservative. All we have to do is look at the 2000 and 2002 Elections to see this.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
