<br>
kebkin wrote:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>So are Ermok's comments liberal rhetoric or fact? You decide.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I think one should investigate the 'great economic turn-around of the last third quarter' in more depth.  The percentage increase was only posted for the last quarter, between July to September, because America experienced a fantastic September.  But I would hardly call one good month out of three a fantastic quarter.<br>
<br>
SergianFV wrote:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As far as &quot;Reaganomics&quot; goes, Reagan proved that supply-side economics and tax rate cuts work.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Reagan got lucky on some accounts, but overall I would say Reaganomics was and is a failure.<br>
<br>
Reagan escaped with his skin because he had Paul Volcker, the Fed chairman at the time, crushing American and its inflation by raising interest rates to near 20%.  It wasn't Reaganomics or the tax cuts that ended the recession of 1981, it was the Fed cutting interest rates from the terrible levels it was raised to to solve for inflation.<br>
<br>
The problem that we are facing nowadays is that Alan Greenspan hasn't been focusing on curbing 'real' inflation.  Alan Greenspan has busied himself stopping 'wage inflation.'  The inflation rates remained at historical low levels during the 1990's, and Greenspan slowed the economic expansion of the United States to so that industry was not forced to raise the wage level of its employees.  American workers earn the same pay today that they were making in 1990.<br>
<br>
But what does that matter you say?  <br>
<br>
Well, even though President Bush passed his 1.35 trillion dollar tax cuts package, his campaign hasn't helped the majority of Americans.  This is why so many people were up in arms that President Bush was giving tax breaks 'to the wealthiest one-two percent' of America.  <br>
<br>
President Bush passed this tax cut under the guise that it would be helping all of America.  Sure, the income tax for everyone has been reduced, but his campaign has quietly raised the payroll tax for Americans.  <br>
<br>
Payroll taxes, Social Security, and Medicare are FLAT TAXES.  There are no write-offs or deductions, and everyone, from Circle K workers to CEOs, are hit with the same percent.  <br>
<br>
But this payroll tax doesn't really effect the richest percent because they don't usually earn most of their income from wages.  They own capital (money that makes more money), which is not subject to payroll taxation.  Capital gains taxes have been steadily reduced to 15% nowadays.  And since all of this ridiculously low taxed capital gain isn't payroll income, the richest percent pays nothing into Medicare or Social Security.  Social Security is actually a regressive flat tax because only the first 76 thousand dollars of wage income is taxed.  So even rich workers are getting a break over the poorer worker.  <br>
<br>
Payroll taxes account for over a third of the federal income (and most of the surpluses in past years) but Bush has never even suggested cutting these taxes or making it more fair for Americans still making the same wage as in 1990.  Couple all of this with the fact that three million Americans have lost their jobs in the last three years.<br>
<br>
I agree with Ermok, Bush is bleeding America dry.  It is not politically appealing to cut social spending.  It would hurt Bush's chances of re-election if he went around claiming that he wants to cut welfare, social security, education, and etc spending.  So he achieves his goals of cutting government spending but hitting it where it hurts.  He is cutting income tax, especially the capital gains tax, in an attempt to starve the government and force IT to do the cutting of social spending itself.  Bush wants the murder committed, but he doesn't want his fingerprints on the murder weapon. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sergianfv>SergianFV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 68<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/3/03 9:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=884.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I pose a question</span><hr size=1> Tax cuts had nothing to do with the economic boom of the 80's?  I'd call it colossal ignorance or colossal arrogance to completely discount the economic impact of millions of people keeping and spending the money that they earned.  I won't argue that the Federal Reserve's rate cuts didn't help,  but it's people that drive capitalism, not the Fed.  The Fed can either assist or hinder the economy in this regard, but it doesn't drive it.  People with money to spend (a little or a lot) do that.  Reagan knew it and proved it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I don't think it was the screaming lefties that swung the vote, it was the spending Benjamins<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Actually, no.  I think the grown-ups are finally waking up and seeing what a mess the kids have made of the house.  Now it's time for the grown-ups to put some common sense back into government.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>President Bush passed his 1.35 trillion dollar tax cuts package<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
First off, this is an incorrect nomenclature.  Tax cuts have never <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>cost</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the government a thing.  They have <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>always</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> resulted in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>increased</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> government revenues.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>...his campaign hasn't helped the majority of Americans<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
It's helped me.  It's helped my business.  It's helped my neighbor's daughter who I hired to help with the extra wholesale and weekend business we've picked up recently.  I'm not sure who you consider to be the &quot;majority.&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>This is why so many people were up in arms that President Bush was giving tax breaks 'to the wealthiest one-two percent' of America<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I think you're watching a bit too much Dan Rather <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Class envy (and envy in general) is a horrible little emotion.  Every bracket got a cut, not just the highest.  They're just not getting pummeled as hard now as the whining-ass class-enviers would like.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>but his campaign has quietly raised the payroll tax for Americans<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If Bush had raised any tax, there would have been nothing quiet about it.  The mainstream media would have hammered him over the head with it.  The only possible bit of traction you may have on this point is the fact that the cap on FICA wages is tied to rises in inflation, which happens every year.  This isn't anything new, and so is irrelevant to the debate.<br>
<br>
The rest of what you say is typical &quot;eat the rich&quot; rot.  We have a tax system that is punitive.  &quot;Progressive&quot; is hardly an accurate term, only in that it progressively punishes you the more successful you become.  But when more than 50% of the total taxes are paid by the wealthiest 4% of the population, there's something wrong.  These are the people that create jobs and create wealth, not some government bureaucrat.  When you reduce the tax burden on everyone, these folks will invariably get to keep a larger &quot;raw dollar&quot; amount than the checkout girl at the supermarket.  But I don't see why this is such a cause for hysterics.<br>
<br>
As for capital gains taxes, when the capital gains tax was lowered in the 90s, it unleashed a flood of capital and, hence, a flood of government revenue as a result.  All those evil rich folk went and got rid of capital that they'd been holding on to because they didn't want to get slammed with the punitive taxes.  But when times are tough (i.e. high capital gains taxes), it's not rich folk that need to sell off capital assets to put their kids through college.<br>
<br>
As far as &quot;bleeding America dry&quot; goes, I'm not sure what you consider to be &quot;America.&quot;  Do you mean the government?  If that's the case, you've totally lost sight of what this country is all about.  But in any case, if that's what you consider to be &quot;America,&quot; then so be it.  As I've said above, government revenues have <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>always</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> gone up when taxes have been lowered.  It happened under Kennedy, it happened under Reagan, and it's already starting to happen under Bush.  Go look up the numbers.  You may be shocked and dismayed.<br>
<br>
