The war was started when Iraq invaded Kuwait, a cease fire was called but there was never an end to the war. When Iraq refused to comply with the cease fire agreements for 12 years the war was resumed. Iraq started the war, no doubt about it.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Actually the recession started during the Bush administration.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
How do you figure? The recession started before Bush came into office, as a matter of fact he was accused of &quot;talking down the economy&quot; because he spoke about it. If you have evidence contrary to this I for one would be interested.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Actually every single new Republican President of the entire century has had a recession his first term.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I would like to know what statistics you are basing this on as most recessions are pretty obvious. Or are you talking about dips in the economy which are common when a new administration takes over because of insecurities in the market? These are not recessions.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Correction- jobless claims are one thing, but the economy is still losing jobs, just at a slower rate.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
You are contradicting yourself here but to put it in perspective, the jobless percentage is going down and we are also becoming more efficient. Win-Win!<br>
